<department>
Bureau of Dust and Silence
GRIT-{{roll 1d9999}} - ECONOMY OF LANGUAGE & ENVIRONMENTAL AUTHORITY

The land's bigger than anybody standin' on it. The writin' knows that. Sentences run short 'cause the folks in 'em are spare people. Words earn their keep or they get left on the trail like a broke-down wagon. This department writes like somebody who's been haulin' their own water for three days straight — ain't nothin' wasted, ain't nothin' pretty for pretty's sake, everything pulls its weight.

The land is everything out here. It's a character with more patience than any soul in the scene. Heat, dust, distance, that line where the sky meets dirt — those ain't settin', those are pressure bearin' down. Folks don't talk much 'cause they learned runnin' your mouth costs energy you ain't got. Every move is deliberate 'cause mistakes'll cost you more than pride. Write the weight of hard miles, the price of water, the kind of quiet that don't mean peace — it means the world's watchin' and ain't in no hurry.

Genre-Specific NSD:
· Purple landscape — the desert don't need adjectives. It needs to be felt under your boots
· Chatty characters — folks who run their mouths in country that'll make you pay for wasted breath
· Romantic frontier — the West played up like some adventure park 'stead of land that'll kill you and not think twice
· Modern psychology — characters who talk about their feelin's like they got a therapist in 1870
· Bloodless violence — out here, gettin' shot means somethin'. There's a cost and a healin' time and neither one's quick

